We have air bags because.... (this applies to severe front end accidents which I believe to be a
majority of bad accidents)

The original type 'manual' seatbelts were &quot;too much trouble&quot; for the average US driver
to use, so the many variations of automatic seatbelts were intorduced.

&quot;They are uncomfortable&quot;
&quot;They wrinkle my clothes&quot;
&quot;I don't want to be trapped after an accident&quot; etc...
There is no replacement for a decent IQ, but I digress...

Another consequence of the fleet fuel mileage requirements was that automobile frames were eliminated.
Now the structural integrity of the vehicle depended on a stamped sheet metal pan instead of a welded
beam structure. Now in frontal collisions these pans break, bend and fail allowing the front section
of the car's body (generally, from the front door posts forward) to move backward into the passenger
compartment. The survivable space that use to exist in real cars no longer existed, so to keep the
passengers from being hit in the face with the front third of the car, air bage were installed.

In modern cars, a seat belt system merely holds the passengers in place as the front of the vehicle
is shoved through their chest. Although air bags help in some of the more moderate to severe accidents,
the most severe accidents leave so little room inside that an air bag is of little consequence.

I worked as a firefighter for 5.5 years and saw many examples of this, and not all were in compact or
sub-comapct cars as you might think. E me if you want me to post some further details on this subject....

DRLs? At whose expense? Motorcyclists. Because American drivers are generally so involved with putting
on their make-up, reading the paper, drinking coffee, changing the CD, or smacking the kids in the back
seat to watch where they are going, autos are now comming equipped with DRLs.

The daytime headlight was one of the few things that motorcyclists had in their favor while trying to avoid
becoming a hood ornament on the next car that happened by. According the the Hurt study:

In the multiple vehicle accidents, the driver of the other vehicle violated the motorcycle right-of-way and
caused the accident in two-thirds of [the accidents studied].

So who wins, who loses? Enough raving for now... Flame away!

