&gt;In article &lt;31929adb.27119 ... @news.globalx.net&gt;, e ... @ingenius.on.ca (Erick Sodhi) writes:

&gt;|&gt; Among the whole pile of reasons why it makes sense to be seen is the
&gt;|&gt; fact DRLs make it easier for other drivers to see you and to judge
&gt;|&gt; your distance.

&gt;Please explain this statement-- it makes no sense to me. It is damn near
&gt;impossible to judge the distance of a car with lights on, since the lights
&gt;are all you see. The image of the headlights is so far behind the car that
&gt;any estimate of distance is a guess. In addition, it is extremely difficult
&gt;to judge the speed of a vehicle with its lights on, for the same reason.
&gt;This makes it more difficult to decide whether to turn left in front of
&gt;someone.

"/> Au contraire. The fact that the headlights are on provides a
consistent reference to the location of the vehicle, especially in
situations in which the ambient lighting may be changing (e.g., when
the approaching vehicle is moving between sunlit and shady areas). If
all you see is the lights, then the car is a good distance away from
you (we're talking daylight driving here, not night) and you've
probably seen him long before you would have otherwise. I'd be
interested in your results from a real-world experiment: go out for a
drive on a high-speed, two lane road during the day; try to guess the
distance and speed of oncoming traffic and see how good your estimate
is for cars with and without headlights on. I guess we're all
different in the way we perceive things because I don't find that the
image of the headlights is behind the vehicle; I find it to be the
best reference point there is. And road safety research bears me out
on this; drivers consistently are better able to judge the whether a
passing manoeuver or entry to a highway is safe based on the distance
of an oncoming vehicle if the oncoming vehicle's headlights are on.
Unfortunately, I don't have a reference to substantiate this since I
threw it out many moons ago, but it's one of the bases upon which the
Canadian and many other countries' DRL laws are based. Anybody out
there work in highway or automotive safety? (BTW, why do you think
trains are required to operate with REALLY bright lights on at all
times?).
Erick
