"/> You haven't been following the debate. This is a known consequence
of the crash testing requirement that the passenger dummy must not
be belted in. To meet the damage requirements, the passenger side
air bag has to inflate faster - if the dummy was correctly belted, they
could use much slower inflation rates. The number of children killed
by fast inflating airbags is reported to be around 27 so far ( almost all
unrestrained ), the number saved?.

The whole issue has been under intense debate between the car
manufacturers ( who cite the current 67% use of seatbeats, compared
to the &lt;20% at the time the requirement was mandated ) and the
safety authorites. The current consequence is to be a multi-million
dollar campaign to teach the public how to strap paasengers and
children in, and to encourage greater use of restraints for children,
while the information on crash testing alternatives is assessed..

You might be interested that here in New Zealand, if a parent is
seen with a child under a certain age in a car, and the child is not
properly restrained ( belted in or approved baby seat ), then the
parent is charged. This law arose from public concern after a
horrific low speed accident where a child was catapulted through
the windscreen and then run over by another car.

