Sigh, yes, that thread again, complete with the usual error.

Once again, a car hitting a rigid barrier and decelerating from X mph
to 0 mph experiences *exactly* the same deceleration as do two identical
cars each approaching a common stationary point at X mph (where they
will collide and come to rest).

The &quot;two cars colliding head-on at X mph&quot; scenario is, however,
comparable to one car traveling at 2*X mph colliding head-on with
an identical but stationary car -- both cars will leave the collision
traveling at X mph (one going forward, one going backward), each having
accelerated (or decelerated) by X mph in the instant of collision.

