The main consideration in firing the airbags is whether the collision is
very &quot;frontal&quot; or not. They try to make them so they won't go off below
approximately 17 MPH. However this decision has to be made in a
microsecond. Is this a low speed collision or just the beginning of a 60
MPH head on? Better safe than sorry. If the system waits too long you may
be against the airbag when it fires, not a good thing. I hear a lot of
bitching on here about airbags, if anybody doesn't want theirs I will
gladly trade them cars. I feel they are definately a valuable safety
feature (when used correctly), but of course like everything not perfect.
I frequently have to work around and remove these things and often my head
is very near one when I am working on wiring under the dash, this worries
me but I am still glad they are there. There have been some very
unfortunate cases where air bags have caused more damage than they have
saved, many due to lack of information or incorrect use. The dynamics of
any crash are impossible to predict but I would rather have the bag than
just a hard dash. To all out there with air bags in your car, please read
your owners manual completely on their use. Please NEVER have a young
child or baby seat in the front of an air bag equipped car unless you know
this is approved on your particular vehicle. ALWAYS use your seat belts
along with the airbag. Be carefull about having items in the front seat
that may cause harm should an airbag deploy. There is new information
about airbags and children available, if someone can post this it would be
appreciated. I believe the NTSB has a web site that may contain this info.
I do have one beef with the car companies, in commercials they show
airbags as a &quot;billowy&quot; pillow that slowly inflates and you softly bounce
on. In reality an airbag deploy is like a shotgun blast, very fast, very
powerful, very unpleasent, but much better than nothing in MOST cases. Way
too many people die in car accidents. A lot of this I blame on the cars
structure. I think the car companies have severe pressure on them to build
light fuel efficient cars and this is the opposite of safe cars. I think
the manufacturers should be given &quot;safety&quot; points that would apply against
CAFE (Corporate Average Fuel Economy) standards. I believe that many
deaths could be avoided if the cars structure protected the occupants
better from &quot;intrusuion&quot; into the passenger compartment. I used to tow
cars for the state and local police and it sickened me to see the
passenger compartment of some cars after an accident. The people didn't
stand a chance, there simply was no room left in the front seat area,
doors had flown open and car bodies ripped wide open. Many people had
died in cars that were easily repairable (very low speed collisions). This
is a disgrace. As an example I read a few years back that a major foreign
car company had purchased the rights to a new invention. This invention
was to pack box type frame members with a special ceramic bead, this made
the frame much stiffer and stronger than it would have been. What was done
with this? The frames were made smaller and lighter (but no stronger) so
