<POSTER> Raj A. Narayan </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 1996-05-30T12:00:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: r ... @po.CWRU.Edu (Raj A. Narayan)
Groups: alt.autos.antique, alt.autos.camaro.firebird, alt.autos.macho-trucks, alt.autos.rod-n-custom, rec.autos.4x4, rec.autos.antique, rec.autos.driving, rec.autos.marketplace, rec.autos.misc, rec.autos.rod-n-custom, rec.autos.tech


I think we're at a point in the airbag discussion where we need to
sort out information from misinformation. Let's take a few points.

1. Airbags reduce injury in a crash.
I would say that in the the case of frontal impacts, undeniably. I'm
most familiar with GM airbags (I used to sell Buicks at a dealership), which
are designed to deploy in a frontal crash within 30 degrees of the straight
ahead position at an impact of 14 mph or greater with an immovable object
(like a wall). Note then, that you will have to hit a parked car at a higher
speed to get the airbag to go off.
Statistically an airbag isn't likely to save your life because a) any
given vehicle is (statistically speaking) likely to have it's airbag go off
in a crash about once every 175 years, and b) most crashes, including frontal
ones are not fatal. The real value of an airbag, IMHO, is that in frontal
crashes (about 30% of total accidents), your injuries are reduced. It's
perhaps the difference between breaking a collar bone and your nose, and
just having a couple bruises.

2. Airbags lower your insurance.
Most of the evidence seems to suggest otherwise. Because airbag
equipped vehicles cost more to fix, insurance companies take this into con-
sideration along with the presumed reduction in medical expense due to reduced
injury. There were a couple insurance companies which actually raised their
rates slightly if the customer ordered the optional passenger side air bag
(optional passenger side air bags are very uncommon, and 1996 models generally
make them either standard or unavailable).

3. Air bags go off unnecessarily.
Possible, but not likely. It is true, however, that an airbag going
off does not mean that if it hadn't, you would have been seriously injured.
The air bag is a supplemental restraint system providing an additional line
of protection against injury. (Where one without a seat belt, incidentally,
and you'll feel like Mike Tyson hit you in the face). The airbag goes off
at a 14 mph impact with a stationary object, a speed chosen because it is
about the point where some people begin to have serious injuries even in
belts. It should be noted that the vast majority of people at this speed
don't suffer serious injury at 14 mph WITHOUT seat belts, but nonetheless,
there are well documented cases of serious injuries and even deaths at
speeds as low as 12 mph (without belt). The point being, 14 mph is a conser-
vative safety cushion designed with the idea that it is better to reduce in-
jury than to reduce damage to the car.

I don't drive a car with an airbag, and it's not one of my priorities
to do so. But I do think that they work in the most likely situations (redu-
cing injury, not saving lives). As a side note, air bags have become standard
in most new cars, while anti-lock brakes are optional on most except for GM
cars. I think this is backward, since most drivers will never use their
airbag, but every winter, I get into situations where anti-lock brakes are
useful. Just a thought.

-- Raj Narayan
