As long as we're debating the relative merits of various safety
technologies, how about let's open the floor and toss-around some ideas
for safe, effective, non-cruddy-looking methods of retrofitting shoulder
belts into older cars that are only equipped with lap belts? Sure, we've
all seen the slap-dash jobs where someone drills a hole in the B-pillar
and puts a through-bolt in, holding some kind of a universal shoulder
belt. I call this kind of job &quot;Slap-dash&quot; because that's what your head
will do when you're in a front-ender and the through-bolt pulls through.
It's necessary to have some kind of reinforcement, but what kind? How can
we do this and not wind up with sloppy- or kludgy-looking welds or
external plates? And how can we do it with existing '70s-'80s stuff so we
don't have to put modern black-and-fluorescent-orange seat belts in
'50s-'60s cars? If it matters, I want to do this on a '62 Dodge Lancer
and a '65 Chrysler Valiant Custom 200. (Canadian model). Both are
4-doors. The Valiant has a wide B-pillar, the Lancer has a narrow one.
One idea that has occurred to me is to pull the headliner and weld-in
reinforcements to the roof for the roof-mounted reels used on mid-late
'70s Oldsmobiles. But the problem is that these require a guide on the
ends of the front seatback, and I'm not sure how I'd add this.
So, the floor is open: anyone?

