"/> I recently did just this with my '68 Charger; the factory shoulder belt
(which was added at the last minute in '68) had been removed because it
was poorly located and difficult to use.

So after my face met the steering wheel during a hit and run last year, I
thought it might be time to install shoulder harnesses.

Instead of bolting them to the floor (which puts stress on the seat and
may result in the seat buckling during an impact), and not wanting to
irreversibly alter the interior with a roll bar, I thought I'd try something
a little different.

So I welded up a bar of 1&quot; square steel pipe that bolts to the former
shoulder belt anchor points. Now I have my 5-point harnesses mounted as
if they were on a full rollcage, but it's easily returnable to &quot;stock&quot; form.
It works quite well (especially coupled with my new bucket seats), though
I find I need to leave the shoulder harnesses off when driving in reverse
or manuevering in tight places. But they go on before I leave the parking lot.

The 3&quot; webbing (and the copious amounts of it) takes a little getting used to,
but I certainly feel safer. And I have no doubt that it _is_ safer.

Looks pretty cool, too ;-)
