"/> The type of &quot;accelerometer&quot; typically used is the &quot;Breed&quot; type. It's
essentially a steel ball and magnet in a tube, with a small space around
the ball to add damping and two electrical contacts at the end opposite
the magnet. This device is only sensitive in one direction (nominally),
so transverse impacts won't trigger it.

If a piezoelectric accelerometer is used, it will still have very little
transverse sensitivity. Rear impacts can be sensed by looking at the
difference in charge; it will be positive one way, negative the other.

Remember, though, that if you are hit on an angle (that is, not straight
on or straight from the side) that's the same as some combination of
straight on and from the side. If the straight-on component is large
enough, the bag will deploy.

